

Everyday Dilemma: Game Design Document
1. Game Overview
Title: Everyday Dilemma

Subtitle: Phishing Awareness Game

Description: A short, realistic choose-your-own-adventure web game that puts university students in real-life phishing situations they face every day. Players make quick decisions under pressure and immediately see the consequences — helping them learn how to spot and avoid phishing without feeling like they’re in a boring lecture.

2. Cyber Safety Topic
Topic: Phishing Awareness

Focus: How to identify suspicious emails, links, messages, and fake websites in a university context.

3. Target Audience
Primary Audience: Coventry University students (age 18–25)

Behaviors: Frequently receive emails from lecturers/IT, use online banking, and submit coursework on Moodle/Canvas.

4. The Problem
Busy students check emails and texts quickly, often thinking “it won’t happen to me”. They are prime targets for phishing attacks such as fake lecturer assignment requests, fake IT support password resets, and fake bank security alerts. One wrong click can lead to stolen university login details, zero marks, or financial loss.

5. Learning Objectives
After playing the game, the player should be able to:

Correctly identify at least three phishing red flags: suspicious sender address, urgent/threatening language, and shortened or fake links.

Choose the safest action in realistic university email, banking, and coursework scenarios.

6. Game Format
Format: Choose-your-own-adventure interactive web game (scenario-based).

7. Core Gameplay Loop
Read a realistic university scenario (email or text).

Choose from 2–3 realistic actions.

Receive immediate feedback + points + clear learning tip.

Move to the next scenario.

Scenarios:
Scenario 1: Urgent Assignment Re-upload Email

Scenario 2: Fake IT Support Password Reset

Scenario 3: Bank Security Alert Text (Smishing)

8. Rules
You play as a 2nd-year Coventry University student during a busy semester.

Read each scenario carefully.

You must choose one action (no going back).

Points are awarded after every choice.

Goal: Reach 80%+ points for the “Safe Semester” ending.

9. Feedback System
After every choice the game instantly shows:

Green check (+25 pts): Correct & safe.

Yellow warning (–5 pts): Risky (if applicable).

Red X (–15 pts): Wrong.

Each feedback includes: An explanation of the exact phishing red flags, a short learning tip, and a realistic “what happened” consequence story.

10. Rewards & Endings
System: Points system with a visual “Semester Health” progress bar.

Endings:

Safe Semester (80%+): You finish the semester successfully.

Stressful Semester (50–79%): Minor problems and stress.

Failed Semester (below 50%): Realistic consequences like lost data, zero marks, or financial issues.

11. Success Measures
Player scores 80% or above to achieve the "Safe Semester" ending.

Player can correctly name the three main phishing red flags.

Post-game reflection question: “What would you do differently next time in real life?”
